@NODE "About_guide" "About this guide"
@TOC "MAIN"



                       @{B}@{U}A brief word about this guide@{UU}@{UB}


@{B}What is it?@{UB}

Basically this is an index of all of the Klondike cardsets available
on the CARD GAMES CD published by PD Soft.

It is sorted into 3 different ways for your convenience - @{"alphabetically" link "index_alpha.guide/main"},
by @{"category" link "index_cat.guide/main"} and by @{"author" link "index_authors.guide/main"}.



@{B}Why write it?@{ub}

I wrote it because I found the organisation of the CD to be absolutely dire.
All of the cardsets were basically lumped together in one directory, with
no way of knowing what the cardsets were, or who they were by unless you
were able to link the readme file with the appropriate cardset.

However, even that slightly difficult task was made near impossible as
a lot of the readme files were missing. The worst example I found was
Rastan's cardsets, as he usually used RASTAN_SAYS_READ_ME_NOW!! as a
standard filename for all of his cardsets, and whoever compiled the
CD didn't bother renaming them to something like RASTAN_DR_WHO_NA.txt or
whatever...

So, I have gone through my large collection of Klondike sets on both
CD and floppy, and have included as many of the readme files as I
could find. Some of them didn't come with any readme's, but I've done
my best.


@{B}How do you use it?@{UB}

Anyone who has used any of the Aminet CDs and/or sites will be able to
identify with my layout. Once you have chosen the way you want to list
the cards (as mentioned above), you will see two groups of text buttons.

On the left you will see the name of the cardset, and on the right is
either README or NO TEXT. Click the left to see the cardset, and the
right to see the readme for that cardset (if it exists)....

There is one extra example you may see where PD Soft have messed up the
organisation, and have not dearchived the cardset from its original
LHA. You will recognise these as they have the word "ARCHIVED" included
in the name field. Viewing these will take a little longer as the
appropriate file (either cardset or readme) has to be dearchived to
RAM.

Note.. If you try to view the cardset from an archive, you will have
to click the "CLEAN UP" button at the far right side, as I couldn't
find any easy way of getting a script to do it as SHOWREKO actually
comes out with an error code which halts the script. I can't understand
why, it just does....



@{B}@{U}EXAMPLES:-@{UB}@{UU}


@{B}1. Click left field for cardset, and right field for text (included on CD).@{UB}

@{"Doctor Who                                   " system "c:showreko cards_cd:klondike-iii/cards/Dr_Who.REKO"} ...... @{"Read Me" system "showguide cards_cd:klondike-iii/readmefiles/rastan_says_read_me_now"}



@{B}2. Click left field for cardset, and right field for text (from this guide).@{UB}

@{"Doctor Who : The Movie (1996)                " system "c:showreko cards_cd:klondike-iii/cards/Dr_Who_Movie.REKO"} ...... @{"Read Me" system "showguide Dr_Who_Movie.txt"}



@{B}3. Click left field for cardset, and right field for no text message.@{UB}

@{"Commodore 64 Loading Screens                 " system "c:showreko cards_cd:klondike-iii/cards/16C-C64.REKO"} ...... @{"No Text" link "NO_TEXT"}



@{B}4. Click left field for cardset, and right field for no text message. @{U}FROM ARCHIVE@{UU}.@{UB}

@{"Castles (archived)                           " system "CASTLES_REKO"} ...... @{"Read Me" system "castles_txt"} ........ @{"CLEANUP" system "delete ram:castles.reko"}

Note.. You should always click the CLEAN UP button once you have viewed a
cardset from within an archive to save memory.
@endnode
	
