@node "problems" "Problems? Let me help!"
@toc "main"



                       @{U}@{B}Problems, problems, problems@{UU}@{UB}



@{B}1. I can't read the READMEs.@{UB}

Make sure that SHOWGUIDE is in the same directory as the INDEX.GUIDE.


@{B}2. I can't read some of the cardsets READMEs.@{UB}

These may be the extra readme files I supplied with this guide. If so,
make sure they are stored in the same directory as the INDEX.GUIDE.


@{B}3. I can't see the archived cardsets.@{UB}

Make sure you have enough memory available. Have you used the CLEAN UP
buttons from previously viewed archived cardsets?

If you cannot see the READMEs for the archived cardsets, try and remember
if you used the -a option when unarchiving this guide? The reason being
that in order to view the archived cardset and/or readme, the guide has
to run a script usually called [cardset]_reko for the cardsets or
[cardset]_txt for the readme.

Check and see if the attributes are set to SCRIPT by either using something
like Directory Opus PROTECT command, or in Workbench select SHOW ALL FILES,
highlighting the file, going to INFO and ticking SCRIPT for each one.


@{B}4. If I run the index from ToolsDaemon, it reloads when I exit it!@{UB}

Make sure that you have it set to run from WB, and that there are NO
parameter brackets (the [] bit) in the line. And no, I don't know why
it does it.


@{B}5. If I run it from a launcher (apart from ToolsDaemon), it doesn't read
the READMEs whether they're on CD or not.@{UB}

Make sure that you have the current directory set to the same directory
as the main INDEX.GUIDE file, otherwise it won't find SHOWGUIDE unless
you have it in your search path (like C:), nor will it find the extra
readme's I've supplied.

This is pure speculation, as I only use Tools Daemon. However, it could
theoretically be a problem.




Before we go, I should say that I'm NOT a programmer. If you happen to
find a program which causes either SHOWREKO or SHOWGUIDE to crash, I'm
very sorry. I didn't write either of these.. I just use them. However,
@{"let me know" link "call_me"} anyway and I'll see about bringing out a new version which
works in some other way (maybe using the slower REKO.Datatype)

Thanks,
Gerard Sweeney.

@endnode
